'''Andrea Nye''' (born 1939) is a feminist philosopher and writer.<ref name="KrikosIngold2004">{{cite book|author1=Linda A. Krikos|author2=Cindy Ingold|title=Women's Studies: A Recommended Bibliography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BFfXsiGWKyIC&pg=PA649|year=2004|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|isbn=978-1-56308-566-6|pages=649–51}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3400300896/nye-andrea.html |title=Nye, Andrea - American Women Writers: A Critical Reference Guide from Colonial Times to the Present &#124; Encyclopedia.com |first= |last= |work=encyclopedia.com |year=2015 |accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>  Nye is a [[Emeritus|Professor Emerita]] at the [[University of Wisconsin–Whitewater|University of Wisconsin&ndash;Whitewater]] for the  Philosophy and Religious Studies Department and an active member of the Women's Studies Department.<ref name="Warren2008">{{cite book|author=Karen J. Warren|title=An Unconventional History of Western Philosophy: Conversations Between Men and Women Philosophers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8zJOQ52E4GMC&pg=PA553|year=2008|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-7425-6460-2|page=553}}</ref> In 1992, Nye received the University of Wisconsin&ndash;Whitewater Award for Outstanding Research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uww.edu/learn/facandstaff/awardresearch|title=UW-Whitewater Award for Outstanding Research|work=University of Wisconsin-Whitewater}}</ref>

==Life and career==
Andrea Nye was born on October 22, 1939, in [[Philadelphia]] to attorney Hamilton Connor and home-maker Florence Deans.<ref name="highbeam.com"/> Nye received  a B. A. in philosophy from [[Radcliffe College]] ([[Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study]]) in 1961 and a Ph.D. in philosophy from the [[University of Oregon]] in 1977.<ref name="highbeam.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2699100120.html|title=Nye, Andrea 1939–|work=HighBeam Research - Cengage Learning}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~coco25/general_files/Participant_Interest98.html|title=Participant Interest 98|work=Dartmouth College}}</ref><ref name="Nye1999">{{cite book|author=Andrea Nye|title=The Princess and the Philosopher: Letters of Elisabeth of the Palatine to René Descartes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_i1_kUBrsEQC&pg=PA187|year=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8476-9265-1|page=187}}</ref> Nye has been affiliated with the University of Wisconsin—Whitewater for decades; first as an assistant professor from 1978 to 1985, then as an associate professor from 1985–1990, followed by a position as a professor of philosophy from 1990–2002.<ref name="highbeam.com"/> Nye has been a  professor emeritus for the philosophy and religious studies department since  2002.<ref name="highbeam.com"/> Andrea Nye is also a member of the Liberal Studies Division at the [[Boston Conservatory]] teaching interdisciplinary courses in the Humanities.<ref name="Moran2008">{{cite book|author=Dermot Moran|title=The Routledge Companion to Twentieth Century Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6u2BAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR11|year=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-42403-0|page=11}}</ref>

Nye's early work in [[philosophy of language]] included a thesis on private language and a monograph on the history of logic from a feminist perspective.<ref name="Bart2000">{{cite book|author=Jody Bart|title=Women Succeeding in the Sciences: Theories and Practices Across Disciplines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=820lRoRr3H8C&pg=PA195|year=2000|publisher=Purdue University Press|isbn=978-1-55753-122-3|page=195}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~koertge/rfemlog.html|title=The Feminist Critique [Repudiation] of Logic|work=Noretta Koertge (Indiana University)}}</ref> In subsequent work, Nye turned more specifically to issues related to gender in language, the place of women in the history of philosophy, and [[feminist theory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/femapproach-analytic/|title=Analytic Feminism|work=Stanford University}}</ref> Reviving the work of neglected or misinterpreted women thinkers was of special interest in later work,<ref name="KrikosIngold2004"/> including translations and commentary on the letters of [[Elisabeth of the Palatinate]] to [[René Descartes]] (''The Princess and the Philosopher''), the political thought of [[Rosa Luxemburg]], [[Hannah Arendt]], and [[Simone Weil]] (''Philosophia'') and most recently, [[Diotima of Mantinea|Diotima]]’s teaching on erotic desire in [[Symposium (Plato)|Plato’s Symposium]] (hl)(''Socrates and Diotima'').<ref name="KrikosIngold2004"/>

