'''Anthony Trevor Cope''' was professor of [[Zulu language|Zulu]] at the [[University of Natal]]. He edited [[Harry Camp Lugg]]'s translation of [[Magema Magwaza Fuze]]'s ''Abantu Abamnyama'' (1922) into English which was published by the University of Natal Press in 1979 as ''The Black People and Whence They Came''.<ref name=camp>[http://campbell.ukzn.ac.za/?q=taxonomy/term/358 Fuze, Magema Magwaza /Papers.] Campbell Collections, University of KwaZulu-Natal. Retrieved 3 August 2018.</ref><ref name="oxf">[https://books.google.com/books?id=39JMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA403 "Fuze, Magema"] by Hlonipha Mokoena in {{cite book|author=[[Emmanuel Kwaku Akyeampong]] & [[Henry Louis Gates Jr.]] (Eds.)|title=Dictionary of African Biography|url=|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press. Vol. 2|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-538207-5|pages=403–405}}</ref>
==Selected publications== * ''Izibongo. Zulu praise-poems''. Collected by [[James Stuart (linguist)|James Stuart]]. Translated by [[D. McK Malcolm|Daniel Malcolm]]. Edited with introductions and annotations by Anthony Trevor Cope. Clarendon Press, Oxford, 1968.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rycroft|first=David|date=1969|title=Review of Izibongo: Zulu Praise-Poems Collected by|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/614051|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London|volume=32|issue=2|pages=438–441}}</ref> * ''A Select Bibliography Relating to the Zulu People of Natal and Zululand''. l974. * ''A Comprehensive Course in the Zulu Language''. University of Natal, 1982. * ''The Black People and Whence They Came''. Magema Magwaza Fuze, translated by Harry Camp Lugg and edited by Anthony Trevor Cope. University of Natal Press, Pietermaritzburg, 1979. (Killie Campbell Africana library. Translation series, No. 1) {{ISBN|0869801678}} * ''Zulu Phonology, Tonology and Tonal Grammar''. 1986. * ''UMamazane = Mamazane''. R.H. Mthembu, translated into English by D.M. Mzolo and Anthony Trevor Cope. Solo Collective, Cowies Hill, South Africa, 2003.
